										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<h3>Isn&#8217;t it comforting to know that things work exactly how they should?</h3>
<p><span id="more-111"></span></p>
<p>It&#8217;s awfully convenient that lasers come in red, green, and blue. This lets us make a bunch of other colors.<br />
According to the laws of eyeballs, combining red and green light makes the light appear yellow. And that&#8217;s exactly what happens.</p>
<div id="attachment_139" style="width: 658px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/IMG_20151021_172316098-e1454943923735.jpg" rel="attachment wp-att-139"><img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-139" decoding="async" class="wp-image-139" src="/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/IMG_20151021_172316098-e1454943923735-1024x865.jpg" alt="Yellow laser" width="648" height="548" srcset="/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/IMG_20151021_172316098-e1454943923735.jpg 1024w, /wp-content/uploads/2016/02/IMG_20151021_172316098-e1454943923735-300x253.jpg 300w, /wp-content/uploads/2016/02/IMG_20151021_172316098-e1454943923735-400x338.jpg 400w" sizes="(max-width: 648px) 100vw, 648px" /></a><p id="caption-attachment-139" class="wp-caption-text">I can&#8217;t believe it&#8217;s not butter!</p></div>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>It&#8217;s worth noting that just because the light <em>looks</em> yellow doesn&#8217;t mean it <em>is</em> yellow. The light is still composed entirely of red and green wavelengths, but due to how our eyes perceive light, it appears yellow. Cameras work the same way.</p>
<p>Here are some more predictably pigmented colors:</p>
<p><a href="/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/IMG_20151021_172510986-e1454944431423.jpg" rel="attachment wp-att-141"><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" class="aligncenter wp-image-141" src="/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/IMG_20151021_172510986-e1454944431423-1024x865.jpg" alt="Aquamarine laser" width="649" height="548" srcset="/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/IMG_20151021_172510986-e1454944431423.jpg 1024w, /wp-content/uploads/2016/02/IMG_20151021_172510986-e1454944431423-300x253.jpg 300w, /wp-content/uploads/2016/02/IMG_20151021_172510986-e1454944431423-400x338.jpg 400w" sizes="(max-width: 649px) 100vw, 649px" /></a><a href="/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/IMG_20151021_172254359-e1454944387353.jpg" rel="attachment wp-att-137"><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" class="aligncenter wp-image-137" src="/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/IMG_20151021_172254359-e1454944387353-1024x865.jpg" alt="Purple laser" width="649" height="548" srcset="/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/IMG_20151021_172254359-e1454944387353.jpg 1024w, /wp-content/uploads/2016/02/IMG_20151021_172254359-e1454944387353-300x253.jpg 300w, /wp-content/uploads/2016/02/IMG_20151021_172254359-e1454944387353-400x338.jpg 400w" sizes="(max-width: 649px) 100vw, 649px" /></a></p>
<div id="attachment_132" style="width: 659px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/IMG_20151021_144504703-e1454944509578.jpg" rel="attachment wp-att-132"><img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-132" decoding="async" loading="lazy" class="wp-image-132" src="/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/IMG_20151021_144504703-e1454944509578-1024x799.jpg" alt="Combination of lasers" width="649" height="506" srcset="/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/IMG_20151021_144504703-e1454944509578.jpg 1024w, /wp-content/uploads/2016/02/IMG_20151021_144504703-e1454944509578-300x234.jpg 300w, /wp-content/uploads/2016/02/IMG_20151021_144504703-e1454944509578-400x312.jpg 400w" sizes="(max-width: 649px) 100vw, 649px" /></a><p id="caption-attachment-132" class="wp-caption-text">And when you combine all three colors, you get white.</p></div>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Although it is strange that my 300mW red laser looks equally bright as my 5mW green one. Maybe physics is broken after all.</p>
<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="/lasers-obey-laws-physics/">Lasers Obey the Laws of Physics</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="/">Blasted Science</a>.</p>
